Sometimes it helps to try out Emacs the way someone with more experience has configured it. There are a number of "starter kits" or "distros" that modify Emacs in different ways. Some are lightweight changes to try to provide better defaults. Others modify Emacs extensively. Whether you're starting out or looking around for inspiration, it might be worth trying out a few to see if any of them fit the way you want to work.

If you use a complex starter kit and encounter something that you want additional help with, try asking the specific community for the starter kit if there is one, or reach out to the author first. If you can't find help that way, then reach out to other Emacs help resources (GetHelp). Make sure to mention which starter kit you're using, how you've modified it, and what you want to do. This is because starter kits can modify a lot of Emacs's behavior, so it helps to ask people with experience with your specific starter kit.

Note: The 'starter kits' listed here are those specifically designed for public use (vs. personal configurations posted online).

= Things to know before you start =

*Basic tutorial:* If you have not yet read the EmacsTutorial, start with that so that you can understand how to use keyboard shortcuts and commands described in the starter kit documentation. If you prefer a webpage, [https://www.gnu.org/software/emacs/tour/ The GNU Emacs Guided Tour] may be useful.

*Git:* Starter kit installation instructions include steps like "Clone this repository" or "Check out this code." If you come from a non-programming background, you might find it useful to first read a tutorial on how to install and use the Git version control system.

* [https://github.com/git-guides/install-git Git Guides - install git · GitHub]
* [https://git-scm.com/book/en/v2/Git-Basics-Getting-a-Git-Repository Git - Getting a Git Repository]
* [https://docs.github.com/en/repositories/creating-and-managing-repositories/cloning-a-repository Cloning a repository - GitHub Docs]

*Your init file:* Starter kits also sometimes ask you to add code to your InitFile (your Emacs configuration file). This file might not exist until you create it. Emacs checks for user configuration in a number of locations, so you might see references to `~/.emacs', `~/.emacs.d/init.el', or `~/.config/emacs/init.el'. If you do not know where your init file is located, you can check the variable `user-init-file' with the following command:

   M-x describe-variable RET user-init-file RET

This will show you the current value of `user-init-file' in the part that says "Its value is ...". Take note of that filename (or select and copy it), then open the file. You can open the file by using the menu bar (File - Open File) or by using `M-x find-file'.

After you make any changes suggested by the starter kit, you can save your init file using the menu bar (File - Save) or using `M-x save-buffer'.

To run the code in your current Emacs, you can use `M-x eval-buffer'. Alternatively, you can use `M-x restart-emacs'. You can also start a separate Emacs instead.

= Choosing a starter kit =

You might want to start by browsing through screenshots or videos about the starter kit to see if it includes the features you are interested in or if it comes with the workflows you are thinking of using.

Here are some questions you can use to help you choose a starter kit:

* What do you want to do with Emacs? Many starter kits are oriented towards a specific purpose, such as writing or programming.
* Are you looking for specific keyboard shortcut schemes? People who are coming from a Vim background might want to use a starter kit that uses EvilMode to set up Vim-based keybindings, such as DoomEmacs or [[Spacemacs]].
* Do you want something that just changes things slightly or something more extensive?

** Minimalist: just a few changes to Emacs that you can use or read through and adapt to your own configuration
